1
00:00:00,385 --> 00:00:27,507
namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambuddhassa namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambuddhassa namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambuddhassa

2
00:00:30,085 --> 00:00:37,899
So just to continue the words that the Buddha used in dependent origination.

3
00:00:38,942 --> 00:00:53,088
So we went through the first parts which are basically to do with how we enter into every moment with this ignorance, this not knowing.

4
00:00:53,406 --> 00:01:04,778
and it creates these sankaras which are the conditions that we end up manufacturing through this misunderstanding.

5
00:01:06,161 --> 00:01:21,878
And there's the given, there's consciousness which is that point of cognition and the body-mind complex and those two remember work on each other, the Buddha said they're like two sheaves

6
00:01:21,858 --> 00:01:26,903
of hey leaning against each other, the one can't arise without the other.

7
00:01:28,545 --> 00:01:39,275
And then we have what the body and mind, what the constituents are, the nāma, the salayata, the six senses, and with that we make contact.

8
00:01:40,938 --> 00:01:46,043
This contact has an object, it has a sense base, and it has that consciousness we're talking about.

9
00:01:46,444 --> 00:01:53,472
And then we give it a tone color, a feeling color, whether it's pleasant, unpleasant, or neutral.

10
00:01:53,492 --> 00:01:57,557
So that's what you enter each moment with, as it were.

11
00:01:57,817 --> 00:02:01,981
That's your given, that's your viparka, that's the product of past action.

12
00:02:02,862 --> 00:02:15,877
Now, this is where the ignorance now strikes again, as it were, underneath the whole problem and produces a certain relationship to what we find as pleasant and unpleasant, and that's your tanha.

13
00:02:16,616 --> 00:02:27,067
So this tanha is translated as craving, which is sometimes a little bit too strong for these little desires we have.

14
00:02:27,146 --> 00:02:32,913
But we include things like addictions and compulsive behaviors in this tanha.

15
00:02:33,973 --> 00:02:40,439
And some people translate it as lack, a sense of lack, like you've got a big hole, you've got to fill it up.

16
00:02:41,121 --> 00:02:45,104
A thirst, another translation you'll come across.

17
00:02:45,203 --> 00:02:47,612
But the usual one you get is craving.

18
00:02:48,576 --> 00:02:54,200
And what that is telling us again is just what our relationship to something is.

19
00:02:54,737 --> 00:03:02,286
And the relationship, remember, is always based on this wrong understanding of seeking happiness in the wrong place, perfect happiness.

20
00:03:03,667 --> 00:03:05,688
So that's your tanha.

21
00:03:06,530 --> 00:03:13,638
And that should become pretty straightforward when you meditate, because when something comes up, you'll see your reaction.

22
00:03:14,338 --> 00:03:17,401
And remember, it's not always craving in a sense of wanting something.

23
00:03:17,421 --> 00:03:18,763
It's not wanting something, too.

24
00:03:18,782 --> 00:03:22,467
So you get resistance and indulgence, resistance and indulgence.

25
00:03:23,931 --> 00:03:29,360
So that's your hate-love dichotomy of life, you see.

26
00:03:29,701 --> 00:03:32,887
And it's at this point that the duality begins to hurt.

27
00:03:33,187 --> 00:03:45,889
We live in a dual world in the sense that it's a multi-complex world, but as soon as we enter into it with this duality of wanting-not-wanting, then it becomes a very unpleasant place for us.

28
00:03:48,146 --> 00:03:50,971
In meditation we're able to see that quite clearly.

29
00:03:51,010 --> 00:04:00,947
But the next step, upadana, is the point where we lose it, where we actually drop into that desire.

30
00:04:01,427 --> 00:04:04,872
That's the becoming of a self, that's the self, the I.

31
00:04:04,853 --> 00:04:23,824
And the Buddha actually calls the Khanda, remember, the five Khandas that we talked about, you know, which are the body, perceptions, feelings, these conditional volitions and consciousness, he called them the Upadana Khanda, the grasping Khanda.

32
00:04:24,665 --> 00:04:50,605
and the thing about this Upadana is that once you enter into it the I, the self becomes and that's the point of suffering actually the tanha in meditation we can see is just a sort of a desire in the heart wanting and not wanting but so long as it's an object so long as we're quite distinct from it it's not actually dukkha, it's not suffering

33
00:04:50,584 --> 00:05:19,983
the suffering comes with the self with the identity with that wanting it's a very lovely little subtle point to sort of grasp and once the I has gone in there I mean I have actually seen it this sucking into an object but it's very difficult to stop then the impulsion the pushing into that wanting a power

34
00:05:21,516 --> 00:05:26,427
While it's tanha, while it's just desire, it only remains potential.

35
00:05:26,588 --> 00:05:27,310
Nothing's happened.

36
00:05:27,370 --> 00:05:32,701
It's just a movement in the mind of resisting or indulging.

37
00:05:33,041 --> 00:05:35,307
But nothing's actually happened.

38
00:05:36,264 --> 00:06:03,014
but as soon as the I gets in there then as I say it's very difficult to stop the next one which is Bhāva the becoming it's at this point that the will comes in and that's your cetana and the Buddha says your cetana your will which is a power is your kamma meaning your action not your kamma in the common ordinary sense of that word that's used in English meaning your comeuppance

39
00:06:02,995 --> 00:06:04,619
Kamma here is an act.

40
00:06:05,521 --> 00:06:08,487
And the act is the becoming of a self again.

41
00:06:09,230 --> 00:06:10,333
So bhava you see.

42
00:06:10,452 --> 00:06:16,367
So every time we fall into the I and do something out of the position of an I, we're becoming.

43
00:06:17,228 --> 00:06:19,754
And that of course is the world of samsara.

44
00:06:20,579 --> 00:06:34,992
So these three words the Buddha tries to capture that whole business of how we create suffering and how we continue to create suffering and the process that we go through.

45
00:06:35,327 --> 00:06:38,031
And you'll see that it's the opposite of language.

46
00:06:38,050 --> 00:06:40,514
Language normally say, I want, I scream.

47
00:06:40,553 --> 00:06:44,038
But actually, I scream, want, I.

48
00:06:44,819 --> 00:06:45,880
And as soon as you get I, get.

49
00:06:46,682 --> 00:06:47,161
And that's it.

50
00:06:48,603 --> 00:06:56,052
That sequence, you see, to see that sequence is to see more and more clearly where the escape is.

51
00:06:56,810 --> 00:07:18,108
if there was no desire before the I, then the escape would be really exceedingly difficult because you'd have to catch this identity extraordinarily quickly but because between the vedana, what we like and dislike, and the I, there lies this potential that we call tanha, the craving

52
00:07:18,494 --> 00:07:28,740
the wanting the not wanting it gives us that if we can see that it gives us that gap in our in our experience

53
00:07:29,648 --> 00:07:43,564
And that's really where we can begin to change ourselves, because when we see that tanha, this craving, call it that, is unwholesome, we can let it pass away, we can let it pass away, we can let it drop away.

54
00:07:43,584 --> 00:07:47,829
And in so doing, remember, it's undermining a habit of craving.

55
00:07:48,629 --> 00:07:54,896
And that is what our sankāras are, our conditional, volitional, volitional conditioning.

56
00:07:56,007 --> 00:08:04,194
It's like these huge circles, they're little circles within this greater circle of dependent origination, all bits feeding off each other.

57
00:08:06,036 --> 00:08:11,500
And there are times when we can see that the desires that come up are actually wholesome.

58
00:08:12,081 --> 00:08:15,305
Okay, they might have a touch of I in it, but the point is that they're wholesome.

59
00:08:16,245 --> 00:08:23,632
And by actually, you know, by putting our will into that, then obviously that's changing our personality.

60
00:08:24,473 --> 00:08:24,612
See?

61
00:08:27,023 --> 00:08:45,960
so those three little links are where the Buddha explains how we carry on creating these sankhāras, these volitional conditionings based on this ground of not knowing, of ignorance, of delusion

62
00:08:48,826 --> 00:09:16,538
so not only in meditation but in daily life you see as soon as you see that I want come up that wanting come up if we can just stop at that moment you see and just catch the craving before we do something that's where we've got the power to change ourselves every time we miss it with either reinforcing an old conditioning which may be unwholesome or

63
00:09:17,226 --> 00:09:21,974
or starting a new one, which may also be wholesome.

64
00:09:21,994 --> 00:09:27,381
So it's a case of bringing this type of mindfulness into virtually everything we do.

65
00:09:28,583 --> 00:09:32,308
And in this way, you know, we just, we slowly change ourselves.

66
00:09:33,711 --> 00:09:37,636
And I think one of the things we come across is the power of these old desires, you know.

67
00:09:38,719 --> 00:09:43,065
They're very, very, they're much, very, very strong, much stronger than we think they are.

68
00:09:45,796 --> 00:09:47,519
So, that's it.

69
00:09:47,659 --> 00:09:49,663
I hope my words have been of some assistance.

70
00:09:51,168 --> 00:09:59,264
May you be fully liberated from all your tanha, upadana, and bhava, sooner rather than later.

